snippet.textDisplay: I don't necessarily disagree with the guys but they are also biased. Shaq is by his own words the most dominant big man in history and Chuck while being short for his position was still a big guy and played in the era where every team was built around the tall dude. The game is so much different today. For instance, MJ was by no means a bad shooter but he made 581 threes his ENTIRE CAREER. Curry has had a season with 402, 69% (nice) of MJ's career total. MJ didn't shoot partly because he had better ways to score but had he played today he would shoot a lot more downtown and that's the point: the era is different and teams see that the three is more than just a "lucky" shot. You don't "live by threes die by threes", today you can actually win championships thru shooting as has GSW shown.

snippet.textDisplay:
You can win with a small ball lineup if your "small" guys have big man skills, e.g. Charles Barkley, Dennis Rodman, Draymond Green, etc. You're still going to need rebounding and defense in a seven-game series against a great team.


The Rockets had a nice game yesterday, but in the playoffs the game slows down and becomes more physical, and their three-point percentages always drop. They will consistently lose in the paint against huge teams, and they're tripling down on thinking their three-point shooting won't go cold at inopportune times (even though it always has thus far).
